# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: synchrophasor-pmu
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission lines transmit either alternating current (AC) or direct current (DC).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] To increase the efficiency of long-distance electric power transmission, the voltage is often increased for transmission, then reduced for local distribution.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This is because higher voltages corresponds to lower currents and lower losses caused by such currents.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The AC voltage level is often changed with transformers.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] A wide area synchronous grid, known as an *interconnection* in North America, directly connects generators delivering AC power with the same relative *frequency* to many consumers.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] North America has four major interconnections: Western, Eastern, Quebec and Texas.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] One grid connects most of continental Europe.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Historically, transmission and distribution lines were often owned by the same company, but starting in the 1990s, many countries liberalized the regulation of the electricity market in ways that led to separate companies handling transmission and distribution.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Most North American transmission lines are high-voltage three-phase AC, although single phase AC is sometimes used in railway electrification systems.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] DC technology is used for greater efficiency over longer distances, typically hundreds of miles.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) technology is also used in submarine power cables (typically longer than 30 miles (50 km)), and in the interchange of power between grids that are not mutually synchronized.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC links stabilize power distribution networks where sudden new loads, or blackouts, in one part of a network might otherwise result in synchronization problems and cascading failures.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electricity is transmitted at high voltages to reduce the energy loss due to resistance that occurs over long distances.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Power is usually transmitted through overhead power lines.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground power transmission has a significantly higher installation cost and greater operational limitations, but lowers maintenance costs.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground transmission is more common in urban areas or visually sensitive locations.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electrical energy must typically be generated at the same rate at which it is consumed.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] A sophisticated control system is required to ensure that power generation closely matches demand.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] If demand exceeds supply, the imbalance can cause generation plant(s) and transmission equipment to automatically disconnect or shut down to prevent damage.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the worst case, this may lead to a cascading series of shutdowns and a major regional blackout.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The US Northeast faced blackouts in 1965, 1977, 2003, and major blackouts in other US regions in 1996 and 2011.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electric transmission networks are interconnected into regional, national, and even continent-wide networks to reduce the risk of such a failure by providing multiple redundant, alternative routes for power to flow should such shutdowns occur.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission companies determine the maximum reliable capacity of each line (ordinarily less than its physical or thermal limit) to ensure that spare capacity is available in the event of a failure in another part of the network.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The conductor consists of seven strands of steel surrounded by four layers of aluminium.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage overhead conductors are not covered by insulation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The conductor material is usually an aluminium alloy, formed of several strands and possibly reinforced with steel strands.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Copper was sometimes used for overhead transmission, but aluminum is lighter, reduces yields only marginally and costs much less.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Overhead conductors are supplied by several companies.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Conductor material and shapes are regularly improved to increase capacity.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Conductor sizes range from 12 mm2 (#6 American wire gauge) to 1,092 mm2 (2,156,000 circular mils area), with varying resistance and current-carrying capacity.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For large conductors (more than a few centimetres in diameter), much of the current flow is concentrated near the surface due to the skin effect.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The center of the conductor carries little current but contributes weight and cost.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus, multiple parallel cables (called bundle conductors) are used for higher capacity.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Bundle conductors are used at high voltages to reduce energy loss caused by corona discharge.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Today, transmission-level voltages are usually considered to be 110 kV and above.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Lower voltages, such as 66 kV and 33 kV, are usually considered subtransmission voltages, but are occasionally used on long lines with light loads.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltages less than 33 kV are usually used for distribution.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltages above 765 kV are considered extra high voltage and require different designs.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Increased ambient temperatures during extreme heat events can reduce the efficiency of electrical transmission and distribution, especially in overhead systems.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thermal expansion causes overhead lines to sag, reducing current flow and increasing the risk of unintended arc discharge if there is vegetation nearby.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Overhead transmission wires depend on air for insulation, requiring that lines maintain minimum clearances.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Adverse weather conditions, such as high winds and low temperatures, interrupt transmission.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Wind speeds as low as 23 knots (43 km/h) can permit conductors to encroach operating clearances, resulting in a flashover and loss of supply.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Oscillatory motion of the physical line is termed conductor gallop or flutter depending on the frequency and amplitude of oscillation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electric power can be transmitted by underground power cables.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground cables take up no right-of-way, have lower visibility, and are less affected by weather.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Cable and excavation costs are much higher than overhead construction.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Faults in buried transmission lines take longer to locate and repair.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In some metropolitan areas, cables are enclosed by metal pipe and insulated with dielectric fluid (usually an oil) that is either static or circulated via pumps.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] If an electric fault damages the pipe and leaks dielectric, liquid nitrogen is used to freeze portions of the pipe to enable draining and repair.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This extends the repair period and increases costs.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The temperature of the pipe and surroundings are monitored throughout the repair period.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground lines are limited by their thermal capacity, which permits less overload or re-rating lines.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Long underground AC cables have significant capacitance, which reduces their ability to provide useful power beyond 50 miles (80 kilometres).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] DC cables are not limited in length by their capacitance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Commercial electric power was initially transmitted at the same voltage used by lighting and mechanical loads.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This restricted the distance between generating plant and loads.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In 1882, DC voltage could not easily be increased for long-distance transmission.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Different classes of loads (for example, lighting, fixed motors, and traction/railway systems) required different voltages, and so used different generators and circuits.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus, generators were sited near their loads, a practice that later became known as distributed generation using large numbers of small generators.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission of alternating current (AC) became possible after Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs built what they called the secondary generator, an early transformer provided with 1:1 turn ratio and open magnetic circuit, in 1881.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first long distance AC line was 34 kilometres (21 miles) long, built for the 1884 International Exhibition of Electricity in Turin, Italy.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] It was powered by a 2 kV, 130 Hz Siemens & Halske alternator and featured several Gaulard transformers with primary windings connected in series, which fed incandescent lamps.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The system proved the feasibility of AC electric power transmission over long distances.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first commercial AC distribution system entered service in 1885 in via dei Cerchi, Rome, Italy, for public lighting.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] It was powered by two Siemens & Halske alternators rated 30 hp (22 kW), 2 kV at 120 Hz and used 19 km of cables and 200 parallel-connected 2 kV to 20 V step-down transformers provided with a closed magnetic circuit, one for each lamp.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] A few months later it was followed by the first British AC system, serving Grosvenor Gallery.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] It also featured Siemens alternators and 2.4 kV to 100 V step-down transformers – one per user – with shunt-connected primaries.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Working to improve what he considered an impractical Gaulard-Gibbs design, electrical engineer William Stanley, Jr. developed the first practical series AC transformer in 1885.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Working with the support of George Westinghouse, in 1886 he demonstrated a transformer-based AC lighting system in Great Barrington, Massachusetts.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] It was powered by a steam engine-driven 500 V Siemens generator.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage was stepped down to 100 volts using the Stanley transformer to power incandescent lamps at 23 businesses over 4,000 feet (1,200 m).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This practical demonstration of a transformer and alternating current lighting system led Westinghouse to begin installing AC systems later that year.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In 1888 the first designs for an AC motor appeared.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] These were induction motors running on polyphase current, independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Practical three-phase motors were designed by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Widespread use of such motors were delayed many years by development problems and the scarcity of polyphase power systems needed to power them.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the late 1880s and early 1890s smaller electric companies merged into larger corporations such as Ganz and AEG in Europe and General Electric and Westinghouse Electric in the US.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] These companies developed AC systems, but the technical difference between direct and alternating current systems required a much longer technical merger.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Alternating current's economies of scale with large generating plants and long-distance transmission slowly added the ability to link all the loads.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] These included single phase AC systems, poly-phase AC systems, low voltage incandescent lighting, high-voltage arc lighting, and existing DC motors in factories and street cars.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In what became a universal system, these technological differences were temporarily bridged via the rotary converters and motor-generators that allowed the legacy systems to connect to the AC grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] These stopgaps were slowly replaced as older systems were retired or upgraded.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first transmission of single-phase alternating current using high voltage came in Oregon in 1890 when power was delivered from a hydroelectric plant at Willamette Falls to the city of Portland 14 miles (23 km) down river.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first three-phase alternating current using high voltage took place in 1891 during the international electricity exhibition in Frankfurt.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 15 kV transmission line, approximately 175 km long, connected Lauffen on the Neckar and Frankfurt.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission voltages increased throughout the 20th century.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] By 1914, fifty-five transmission systems operating at more than 70 kV were in service.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The highest voltage then used was 150 kV.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Interconnecting multiple generating plants over a wide area reduced costs.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The most efficient plants could be used to supply varying loads during the day.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Reliability was improved and capital costs were reduced, because stand-by generating capacity could be shared over many more customers and a wider area.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Remote and low-cost sources of energy, such as hydroelectric power or mine-mouth coal, could be exploited to further lower costs.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The 20th century's rapid industrialization made electrical transmission lines and grids critical infrastructure.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Interconnection of local generation plants and small distribution networks was spurred by World War I, when large electrical generating plants were built by governments to power munitions factories.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] These networks use components such as power lines, cables, circuit breakers, switches and transformers.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission network is usually administered on a regional basis by an entity such as a regional transmission organization or transmission system operator.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission efficiency is improved at higher voltage and lower current.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The reduced current reduces heating losses.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Joule's first law states that energy losses are proportional to the square of the current.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus, reducing the current by a factor of two lowers the energy lost to conductor resistance by a factor of four for any given size of conductor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The optimum size of a conductor for a given voltage and current can be estimated by Kelvin's law for conductor size, which states that size is optimal when the annual cost of energy wasted in resistance is equal to the annual capital charges of providing the conductor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] At times of lower interest rates and low commodity costs, Kelvin's law indicates that thicker wires are optimal.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Otherwise, thinner conductors are indicated.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Since power lines are designed for long-term use, Kelvin's law is used in conjunction with long-term estimates of the price of copper and aluminum as well as interest rates.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Higher voltage is achieved in AC circuits by using a *step-up transformer*.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) systems require relatively costly conversion equipment that may be economically justified for particular projects such as submarine cables and longer distance high capacity point-to-point transmission.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC is necessary for sending energy between unsynchronized grids.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] A transmission grid is a network of power stations, transmission lines, and substations.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Energy is usually transmitted within a grid with three-phase AC.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Single-phase AC is used only for distribution to end users since it is not usable for large polyphase induction motors.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the 19th century, two-phase transmission was used but required either four wires or three wires with unequal currents.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Higher order phase systems require more than three wires, but deliver little or no benefit.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] While the price of generating capacity is high, energy demand is variable, making it often cheaper to import needed power than to generate it locally.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Because loads often rise and fall together across large areas, power often comes from distant sources.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Because of the economic benefits of load sharing, wide area transmission grids may span countries and even continents.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Interconnections between producers and consumers enables power to flow even if some links are inoperative.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The slowly varying portion of demand is known as the *base load* and is generally served by large facilities with constant operating costs, termed firm power.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Such facilities are nuclear, coal or hydroelectric, while other energy sources such as concentrated solar thermal and geothermal power have the potential to provide firm power.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Renewable energy sources, such as solar photovoltaics, wind, wave, and tidal, are, due to their intermittency, not considered to be firm.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The remaining or *peak* power demand, is supplied by peaking power plants, which are typically smaller, faster-responding, and higher cost sources, such as combined cycle or combustion turbine plants typically fueled by natural gas.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] New York often buys over 1000 MW of low-cost hydropower from Canada.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Local sources (even if more expensive and infrequently used) can protect the power supply from weather and other disasters that can disconnect distant suppliers.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Hydro and wind sources cannot be moved closer to big cities, and solar costs are lowest in remote areas where local power needs are nominal.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Connection costs can determine whether any particular renewable alternative is economically realistic.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Costs can be prohibitive for transmission lines, but high capacity, long distance super grid transmission network costs could be recovered with modest usage fees.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] At power stations, power is produced at a relatively low voltage between about 480 V and 22 kV, depending on the size of the unit.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The voltage is then stepped up by the power station transformer to a higher voltage (100 kV to 1,000 kV AC) for transmission.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the United States, power transmission is, variously, 230 kV to 500 kV, with less than 230 kV or more than 500 kV as exceptions.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The Western Interconnection has two primary interchange voltages: 500 kV AC at 60 Hz, and ±500 kV (1,000 kV net) DC from North to South (Columbia River to Southern California) and Northeast to Southwest (Utah to Southern California).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The 287.5 kV (Hoover Dam to Los Angeles line, via Victorville) and 345 kV (Arizona Public Service (APS) line) are local standards, both of which were implemented before 500 kV became practical.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmitting electricity at high voltage reduces the fraction of energy lost to Joule heating, which varies by conductor type, the current, and the transmission distance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For example, a 100 miles (160 km) span at 765 kV carrying 1000 MW of power can have losses of 0.5% to 1.1%.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 345 kV line carrying the same load across the same distance has losses of 4.2%.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For a given amount of power, a higher voltage reduces the current and thus the resistive losses.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For example, raising the voltage by a factor of 10 reduces the current by a corresponding factor of 10 and therefore the $I^{2}R$ losses by a factor of 100, provided the same sized conductors are used in both cases.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Even if the conductor size (cross-sectional area) is decreased ten-fold to match the lower current, the $I^{2}R$ losses are still reduced ten-fold using the higher voltage.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] While power loss can also be reduced by increasing the wire's conductance (by increasing its cross-sectional area), larger conductors are heavier and more expensive.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] And since conductance is proportional to cross-sectional area, resistive power loss is only reduced proportionally with increasing cross-sectional area, providing a much smaller benefit than the squared reduction provided by multiplying the voltage.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Long-distance transmission is typically done with overhead lines at voltages of 115 to 1,200 kV.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] At higher voltages, where more than 2,000 kV exists between conductor and ground, corona discharge losses are so large that they can offset the lower resistive losses in the line conductors.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Measures to reduce corona losses include larger conductor diameter, hollow cores or conductor bundles.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Factors that affect resistance and thus loss include temperature, spiraling, and the skin effect.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Spiraling, which refers to the way stranded conductors spiral about the center, also contributes to increases in conductor resistance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The skin effect causes the effective resistance to increase at higher AC frequencies.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Corona and resistive losses can be estimated using a mathematical model.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] US transmission and distribution losses were estimated at 6.6% in 1997, 6.5% in 2007 and 5% from 2013 to 2019.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In general, losses are estimated from the discrepancy between power produced (as reported by power plants) and power sold; the difference constitutes transmission and distribution losses, assuming no utility theft occurs.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] As of 1980, the longest cost-effective distance for DC transmission was 7,000 kilometres (4,300 miles).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For AC it was 4,000 kilometres (2,500 miles), though US transmission lines are substantially shorter.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In any AC line, conductor inductance and capacitance can be significant.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Currents that flow solely in reaction to these properties, (which together with the resistance define the impedance) constitute reactive power flow, which transmits no power to the load.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] These reactive currents, however, cause extra heating losses.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The ratio of real power transmitted to the load to apparent power (the product of a circuit's voltage and current, without reference to phase angle) is the power factor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] As reactive current increases, reactive power increases and power factor decreases.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For transmission systems with low power factor, losses are higher than for systems with high power factor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Utilities add capacitor banks, reactors and other components (such as phase-shifters; static VAR compensators; and flexible AC transmission systems, FACTS) throughout the system help to compensate for the reactive power flow, reduce the losses in power transmission and stabilize system voltages.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] These measures are collectively called 'reactive support'.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Current flowing through transmission lines induces a magnetic field that surrounds the lines of each phase and affects the inductance of the surrounding conductors of other phases.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The conductors' mutual inductance is partially dependent on the physical orientation of the lines with respect to each other.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Three-phase lines are conventionally strung with phases separated vertically.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The mutual inductance seen by a conductor of the phase in the middle of the other two phases is different from the inductance seen on the top/bottom.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Unbalanced inductance among the three conductors is problematic because it may force the middle line to carry a disproportionate amount of the total power transmitted.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Similarly, an unbalanced load may occur if one line is consistently closest to the ground and operates at a lower impedance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Because of this phenomenon, conductors must be periodically transposed along the line so that each phase sees equal time in each relative position to balance out the mutual inductance seen by all three phases.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] To accomplish this, line position is swapped at specially designed transposition towers at regular intervals along the line using various transposition schemes.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Subtransmission runs at relatively lower voltages.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] It is uneconomical to connect all distribution substations to the high main transmission voltage, because that equipment is larger and more expensive.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Typically, only larger substations connect with this high voltage.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage is stepped down before the current is sent to smaller substations.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Subtransmission circuits are usually arranged in loops so that a single line failure does not stop service to many customers for more than a short time.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Loops can be *normally closed*, where loss of one circuit should result in no interruption, or *normally open* where substations can switch to a backup supply.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] While subtransmission circuits are usually carried on overhead lines, in urban areas buried cable may be used.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The lower-voltage subtransmission lines use less right-of-way and simpler structures; undergrounding is less difficult.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] No fixed cutoff separates subtransmission and transmission, or subtransmission and distribution.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltages of 69 kV, 115 kV, and 138 kV are often used for subtransmission in North America.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] As power systems evolved, voltages formerly used for transmission were used for subtransmission, and subtransmission voltages became distribution voltages.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Like transmission, subtransmission moves relatively large amounts of power, and like distribution, subtransmission covers an area instead of just point-to-point.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Substation transformers reduce the voltage to a lower level for distribution to customers.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This distribution is accomplished with a combination of sub-transmission (33 to 138 kV) and distribution (3.3 to 25 kV).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Finally, at the point of use, the energy is transformed to end-user voltage (100 to 4160 volts).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage power transmission allows for lesser resistive losses over long distances.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This efficiency delivers a larger proportion of the generated power to the loads.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In a simplified model, the grid delivers electricity from an ideal voltage source with voltage V , delivering a power $P_{V}$ ) to a single point of consumption, modelled by a resistance R , when the wires are long enough to have a significant resistance $R_{C}$ .
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] If the resistances are in series with no intervening transformer, the circuit acts as a voltage divider, because the same current $I={\frac {V}{R+R_{C}}}$ runs through the wire resistance and the powered device.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For $a>1$ (i.e. conversion of high voltage to low voltage near the consumption point), a larger fraction of the generator's power is transmitted to the consumption point and a lesser fraction is lost to Joule heating.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The terminal characteristics of the transmission line are the voltage and current at the sending (S) and receiving (R) ends.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The line is assumed to be a reciprocal, symmetrical network, meaning that the receiving and sending labels can be switched with no consequence.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The parameters *A*, *B*, *C*, and *D* differ depending on how the desired model handles the line's resistance (*R*), inductance (*L*), capacitance (*C*), and shunt (parallel, leak) conductance *G*.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The four main models are the short line approximation, the medium line approximation, the long line approximation (with distributed parameters), and the lossless line.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In such models, a capital letter such as *R* refers to the total quantity summed over the line and a lowercase letter such as *c* refers to the per-unit-length quantity.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The lossless line approximation is the least accurate; it is typically used on short lines where the inductance is much greater than the resistance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For this approximation, the voltage and current are identical at the sending and receiving ends.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The characteristic impedance is pure real, which means resistive for that impedance, and it is often called surge impedance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] When a lossless line is terminated by surge impedance, the voltage does not drop.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Though the phase angles of voltage and current are rotated, the magnitudes of voltage and current remain constant along the line.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For load > SIL, the voltage drops from sending end and the line *consumes* VARs.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For load < SIL, the voltage increases from the sending end, and the line *generates* VARs.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The short line approximation is normally used for lines shorter than 80 km (50 mi).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] There, only a series impedance *Z* is considered, while *C* and *G* are ignored.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The final result is that A = D = 1 per unit, B = Z Ohms, and C = 0.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The medium line approximation is used for lines running between 80 and 250 km (50 and 155 mi).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The series impedance and the shunt (current leak) conductance are considered, placing half of the shunt conductance at each end of the line.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This circuit is often referred to as a *nominal *π* (pi)* circuit because of the shape (*π*) that is taken on when leak conductance is placed on both sides of the circuit diagram.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The long line model is used when a higher degree of accuracy is needed or when the line under consideration is more than 250 km (160 mi) long.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Series resistance and shunt conductance are considered to be distributed parameters, such that each differential length of the line has a corresponding differential series impedance and shunt admittance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The following result can be applied at any point along the transmission line, where $\gamma$ is the propagation constant.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] To find the voltage and current at the end of the long line, x should be replaced with l (the line length) in all parameters of the transmission matrix.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This model applies the Telegrapher's equations.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) is used to transmit large amounts of power over long distances or for interconnections between asynchronous grids.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] When electrical energy is transmitted over very long distances, the power lost in AC transmission becomes appreciable and it is less expensive to use direct current instead.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For a long transmission line, these lower losses (and reduced construction cost of a DC line) can offset the cost of the required converter stations at each end.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC is used for long submarine cables where AC cannot be used because of cable capacitance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In these cases special high-voltage cables are used.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Submarine connections up to 600 kilometres (370 mi) in length have been deployed.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC links can be used to control grid problems.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The power transmitted by an AC line increases as the phase angle between source end voltage and destination ends increases, but too large a phase angle allows the systems at either end to fall out of step.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Since the power flow in a DC link is controlled independently of the phases of the AC networks that it connects, this phase angle limit does not exist, and a DC link is always able to transfer its full rated power.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] A DC link therefore stabilizes the AC grid at either end, since power flow and phase angle can then be controlled independently.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] As an example, to adjust the flow of AC power on a hypothetical line between Seattle and Boston would require adjustment of the relative phase of the two regional electrical grids.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This is an everyday occurrence in AC systems, but one that can become disrupted when AC system components fail and place unexpected loads on the grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] (and possibly in other cooperating cities along the transmission route).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Such a system could be less prone to failure if parts of it were suddenly shut down.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] One example of a long DC transmission line is the Pacific DC Intertie located in the Western United States.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The amount of power that can be sent over a transmission line varies with the length of the line.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The heating of short line conductors due to line losses sets a thermal limit.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] If too much current is drawn, conductors may sag too close to the ground, or conductors and equipment may overheat.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For intermediate-length lines on the order of 100 kilometres (62 miles), the limit is set by the voltage drop in the line.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For longer AC lines, system stability becomes the limiting factor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Approximately, the power flowing over an AC line is proportional to the cosine of the phase angle of the voltage and current at the ends.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This angle varies depending on system loading.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] It is undesirable for the angle to approach 90 degrees, as the power flowing decreases while resistive losses remain.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The product of line length and maximum load is approximately proportional to the square of the system voltage.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Series capacitors or phase-shifting transformers are used on long lines to improve stability.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC lines are restricted only by thermal and voltage drop limits, since the phase angle is not material.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Understanding the temperature distribution along the cable route became possible with the introduction of distributed temperature sensing (DTS) systems that measure temperatures all along the cable.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Without them maximum current was typically set as a compromise between understanding of operation conditions and risk minimization.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This monitoring solution uses passive optical fibers as temperature sensors, either inside a high-voltage cable or externally mounted on the cable insulation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] For overhead cables the fiber is integrated into the core of a phase wire.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The integrated Dynamic Cable Rating (DCR)/Real Time Thermal Rating (RTTR) solution makes it possible to run the network to its maximum.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] It allows the operator to predict the behavior of the transmission system to reflect major changes to its initial operating conditions.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Some utilities have embraced reconductoring to handle the increase in electricity production.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Reconductoring is the replacement-in-place of existing transmission lines with higher-capacity lines.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Adding transmission lines is difficult due to cost, permit intervals, and local opposition.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Reconductoring has the potential to double the amount of electricity that can travel across a transmission line.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 2024 report found the United States behind countries like Belgium and the Netherlands in adoption of this technique to accommodate electrification and renewable energy.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In April 2022, the Biden Administration streamlined environmental reviews for such projects, and in May 2022 announced competitive grants for them funded by the 2021 Bipartisan Infrastructure Law and 2022 Inflation Reduction Act.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The rate of transmission expansion needs to double to support ongoing electrification and reach emission reduction targets.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] As of 2022, more than 10,000 power plant and energy storage projects were awaiting permission to connect to the US grid — 95% were zero-carbon resources.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] New power lines can take 10 years to plan, permit, and build.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Traditional power lines use a steel core surrounded by aluminum strands (Aluminium-conductor steel-reinforced cable).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Replacing the steel with a lighter, stronger composite material such as carbon fiber (ACCC conductor) allows lines to operate at higher temperatures, with less sag, and doubled transmission capacity.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Lowering line sag at high temperatures can prevent wildfires from starting when power lines touch dry vegetation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Although advanced lines can cost 2-4x more than steel, total reconductoring costs are less than half of a new line, given savings in time, land acquisition, permitting, and construction.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] A reconductoring project in southeastern Texas upgraded 240 miles of transmission lines at a cost of $900,000 per mile, versus a 3,600-mile greenfield project that averaged $1.9 million per mile.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] To ensure safe and predictable operation, system components are controlled with generators, switches, circuit breakers and loads.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The voltage, power, frequency, load factor, and reliability capabilities of the transmission system are designed to provide cost effective performance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission system provides for base load and peak load capability, with margins for safety and fault tolerance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Peak load times vary by region largely due to the industry mix.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In hot and cold climates home air conditioning and heating loads affect the overall load.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] They are typically highest in the late afternoon in the hottest part of the year and in mid-mornings and mid-evenings in the coldest part of the year.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Power requirements vary by season and time of day.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Distribution system designs always take the base load and the peak load into consideration.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission system usually does not have a large buffering capability to match loads with generation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus generation has to be kept matched to the load, to prevent overloading generation equipment.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Multiple sources and loads can be connected to the transmission system and they must be controlled to provide orderly transfer of power.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In centralized power generation, only local control of generation is necessary.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This involves synchronization of the generation units.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In distributed power generation the generators are geographically distributed and the process to bring them online and offline must be carefully controlled.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The load control signals can either be sent on separate lines or on the power lines themselves.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage and frequency can be used as signaling mechanisms to balance the loads.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In voltage signaling, voltage is varied to increase generation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The power added by any system increases as the line voltage decreases.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This arrangement is stable in principle.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage-based regulation is complex to use in mesh networks, since the individual components and setpoints would need to be reconfigured every time a new generator is added to the mesh.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In frequency signaling, the generating units match the frequency of the power transmission system.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In droop speed control, if the frequency decreases, the power is increased.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Wind turbines, vehicle-to-grid, virtual power plants, and other locally distributed storage and generation systems can interact with the grid to improve system operation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Internationally, a slow move from a centralized to decentralized power systems have taken place.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The main draw of locally distributed generation systems is that they reduce transmission losses by leading to consumption of electricity closer to where it was produced.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Under excess load conditions, the system can be designed to fail incrementally rather than all at once.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Brownouts occur when power supplied drops below the demand.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Blackouts occur when the grid fails completely.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Rolling blackouts (also called load shedding) are intentionally engineered electrical power outages, used to distribute insufficient power to various loads in turn.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Grid operators require reliable communications to manage the grid and associated generation and distribution facilities.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Fault-sensing protective relays at each end of the line must communicate to monitor the flow of power so that faulted conductors or equipment can be quickly de-energized and the balance of the system restored.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Protection of the transmission line from short circuits and other faults is usually so critical that common carrier telecommunications are insufficiently reliable, while in some remote areas no common carrier is available.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Rarely, and for short distances, pilot-wires are strung along the transmission line path.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Leased circuits from common carriers are not preferred since availability is not under control of the operator.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission lines can be used to carry data: this is called power-line carrier, or power-line communication (PLC).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] PLC signals can be easily received with a radio in the long wave range.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Optical fibers can be included in the stranded conductors of a transmission line, in the overhead shield wires.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] These cables are known as optical ground wire (*OPGW*).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Sometimes a standalone cable is used, all-dielectric self-supporting (*ADSS*) cable, attached to the transmission line cross arms.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Some jurisdictions, such as Minnesota, prohibit energy transmission companies from selling surplus communication bandwidth or acting as a telecommunications common carrier.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Where the regulatory structure permits, the utility can sell capacity in extra dark fibers to a common carrier.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electricity transmission is generally considered to be a natural monopoly, but one that is not inherently linked to generation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Many countries regulate transmission separately from generation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Spain was the first country to establish a regional transmission organization.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In that country, transmission operations and electricity markets are separate.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission system operator is Red Eléctrica de España (REE) and the wholesale electricity market operator is Operador del Mercado Ibérico de Energía – Polo Español, S.A.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Spain's transmission system is interconnected with those of France, Portugal, and Morocco.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The establishment of RTOs in the United States was spurred by the FERC's Order 888, *Promoting Wholesale Competition Through Open Access Non-discriminatory Transmission Services by Public Utilities; Recovery of Stranded Costs by Public Utilities and Transmitting Utilities*, issued in 1996.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the United States and parts of Canada, electric transmission companies operate independently of generation companies, but in the Southern United States vertical integration is intact.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In regions of separation, transmission owners and generation owners continue to interact with each other as market participants with voting rights within their RTO.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] RTOs in the United States are regulated by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Merchant transmission projects in the United States include the Cross Sound Cable from Shoreham, New York to New Haven, Connecticut, Neptune RTS Transmission Line from Sayreville, New Jersey, to New Bridge, New York, and Path 15 in California.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Additional projects are in development or have been proposed throughout the United States, including the Lake Erie Connector, an underwater transmission line proposed by ITC Holdings Corp., connecting Ontario to load serving entities in the PJM Interconnection region.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Australia has one unregulated or market interconnector – Basslink – between Tasmania and Victoria.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Two DC links originally implemented as market interconnectors, Directlink and Murraylink, were converted to regulated interconnectors.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] A major barrier to wider adoption of merchant transmission is the difficulty in identifying who benefits from the facility so that the beneficiaries pay the toll.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Also, it is difficult for a merchant transmission line to compete when the alternative transmission lines are subsidized by utilities with a monopolized and regulated rate base.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the United States, the FERC's Order 1000, issued in 2010, attempted to reduce barriers to third party investment and creation of merchant transmission lines where a public policy need is found.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The cost of high voltage transmission is comparatively low, compared to all other costs constituting consumer electricity bills.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the UK, transmission costs are about 0.2 p per kWh compared to a delivered domestic price of around 10 p per kWh.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The level of capital expenditure in the electric power T&D equipment market was estimated to be $128.9 bn in 2011.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Mainstream scientific evidence suggests that low-power, low-frequency, electromagnetic radiation associated with household currents and high transmission power lines does not constitute a short- or long-term health hazard.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Some studies failed to find any link between living near power lines and developing any sickness or diseases, such as cancer.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 1997 study reported no increased risk of cancer or illness from living near a transmission line.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Other studies, however, reported statistical correlations between various diseases and living or working near power lines.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] No adverse health effects have been substantiated for people not living close to power lines.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The New York State Public Service Commission conducted a study to evaluate potential health effects of electric fields.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The study measured the electric field strength at the edge of an existing right-of-way on a 765 kV transmission line.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The field strength was 1.6 kV/m, and became the interim maximum strength standard for new transmission lines in New York State.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The opinion also limited the voltage of new transmission lines built in New York to 345 kV.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] On September 11, 1990, after a similar study of magnetic field strengths, the NYSPSC issued their *Interim Policy Statement on Magnetic Fields*.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] This policy established a magnetic field standard of 200 mG at the edge of the right-of-way using the winter-normal conductor rating.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] As a comparison with everyday items, a hair dryer or electric blanket produces a 100 mG – 500 mG magnetic field.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Applications for a new transmission line typically include an analysis of electric and magnetic field levels at the edge of rights-of-way.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Public utility commissions typically do not comment on health impacts.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Biological effects have been established for acute high level exposure to magnetic fields above 100 μT (1 G) (1,000 mG).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] These levels exceed average residential power-frequency magnetic fields in homes, which are about 0.07 μT (0.7 mG) in Europe and 0.11 μT (1.1 mG) in North America.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] The Earth's natural geomagnetic field strength varies over the surface of the planet between 0.035 mT and 0.07 mT (35 μT – 70 μT or 350 mG – 700 mG) while the international standard for continuous exposure is set at 40 mT (400,000 mG or 400 G) for the general public.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p01] Tree growth regulators and herbicides may be used in transmission line right of ways, which may have health effects.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] In some countries where electric locomotives or electric multiple units run on low frequency AC power, separate single phase traction power networks are operated by the railways.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] Prime examples are countries such as Austria, Germany and Switzerland that utilize AC technology based on 16 2*/*3 Hz.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] Norway and Sweden also use this frequency but use conversion from the 50 Hz public supply; Sweden has a 16 2*/*3 Hz traction grid but only for part of the system.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] High-temperature superconductors (HTS) promise to revolutionize power distribution by providing lossless transmission.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] The development of superconductors with transition temperatures higher than the boiling point of liquid nitrogen has made the concept of superconducting power lines commercially feasible, at least for high-load applications.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] It has been estimated that waste would be halved using this method, since the necessary refrigeration equipment would consume about half the power saved by the elimination of resistive losses.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] Companies such as Consolidated Edison and American Superconductor began commercial production of such systems in 2007.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] Superconducting cables are particularly suited to high load density areas such as the business district of large cities, where purchase of an easement for cables is costly.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] Single-wire earth return (SWER) or single-wire ground return is a single-wire transmission line for supplying single-phase electrical power to remote areas at low cost.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] It is principally used for rural electrification, but also finds use for larger isolated loads such as water pumps.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] Single-wire earth return is also used for HVDC over submarine power cables.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] Both Nikola Tesla and Hidetsugu Yagi attempted to devise systems for large scale wireless power transmission in the late 1800s and early 1900s, without commercial success.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] In November 2009, LaserMotive won the NASA 2009 Power Beaming Challenge by powering a cable climber 1 km vertically using a ground-based laser transmitter.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] The system produced up to 1 kW of power at the receiver end.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] In August 2010, NASA contracted with private companies to pursue the design of laser power beaming systems to power low earth orbit satellites and to launch rockets using laser power beams.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] Wireless power transmission has been studied for transmission of power from solar power satellites to the earth.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] A high power array of microwave or laser transmitters would beam power to a rectenna.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] Major engineering and economic challenges face any solar power satellite project.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] The federal government of the United States stated that the American power grid was susceptible to cyber-warfare.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] The United States Department of Homeland Security works with industry to identify vulnerabilities and to help industry enhance the security of control system networks.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] In June 2019, Russia conceded that it was "possible" its electrical grid is under cyber-attack by the United States.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electric-power-transmission-p02] *The New York Times* reported that American hackers from the United States Cyber Command planted malware potentially capable of disrupting the Russian electrical grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] An **electrical grid** (or **electricity network**) is an interconnected network for electricity delivery from producers to consumers.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Electrical grids consist of power stations, electrical substations to step voltage up or down, electric power transmission to carry power over long distances, and finally electric power distribution to customers.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In that last step, voltage is stepped down again to the required service voltage.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Power stations are typically built close to energy sources and far from densely populated areas.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Electrical grids vary in size and can cover whole countries or continents.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] From small to large there are microgrids, wide area synchronous grids, and super grids.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The combined transmission and distribution network is part of electricity delivery, known as the *power grid*.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Grids are nearly always synchronous, meaning all distribution areas operate with three phase alternating current (AC) frequencies synchronized (so that voltage swings occur at almost the same time).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] This allows transmission of AC power throughout the area, connecting the electricity generators with consumers.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Grids can enable more efficient electricity markets.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Although electrical grids are widespread, as of 2016, 1.4 billion people worldwide were not connected to an electricity grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] As electrification increases, the number of people with access to grid electricity is growing.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] About 840 million people (mostly in Africa), which is ca.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] 11% of the World's population, had no access to grid electricity in 2017, down from 1.2 billion in 2010.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Electrical grids can be prone to malicious intrusion or attack; thus, there is a need for electric grid security.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Also as electric grids modernize and introduce computer technology, cyber threats start to become a security risk.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Particular concerns relate to the more complex computer systems needed to manage grids.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] A microgrid is a local grid that is usually part of the regional wide-area synchronous grid, but which can disconnect and operate autonomously.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] It might do this in times when the main grid is affected by outages.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] This is known as islanding, and it might run indefinitely on its own resources.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Compared to larger grids, microgrids typically use a lower voltage distribution network and distributed generators.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Microgrids may not only be more resilient, but may be cheaper to implement in isolated areas.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] A design goal is that a local area produces all of the energy it uses.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] A *wide area synchronous grid* (also called an "interconnection" in North America) is an electrical grid at a regional scale or greater that operates at a synchronized frequency and is electrically tied together during normal system conditions.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] For example, there are four major interconnections in North America (the Western Interconnection, the Eastern Interconnection, the Quebec Interconnection and the Texas Interconnection).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In Europe, one large grid connects most of Western Europe.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] These are also known as synchronous zones, the largest of which is the synchronous grid of Continental Europe (ENTSO-E) with 667 gigawatts (GW) of generation, and the widest region served being that of the IPS/UPS system serving countries of the former Soviet Union.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Synchronous grids with ample capacity facilitate electricity market trading across wide areas.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In the ENTSO-E in 2008, over 350,000 megawatt hours were sold per day on the European Energy Exchange (EEX).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Each of the interconnects in North America are run at a nominal 60 Hz, while those of Europe run at 50 Hz.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] One disadvantage of a wide-area synchronous grid is that problems in one part can have repercussions across the whole grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] For example, in 2018, Kosovo used more power than it generated due to a dispute with Serbia, leading to the phase across the whole synchronous grid of Continental Europe lagging behind what it should have been.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] This caused certain kinds of clocks to become six minutes slow.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] A *super grid* or *supergrid* is a wide-area transmission network that is intended to make possible the trade of high volumes of electricity across great distances.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] It is sometimes also referred to as a *mega grid*.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Super grids can support a global energy transition by smoothing local fluctuations of wind energy and solar energy.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In this context, they are considered as a key technology to mitigate global warming.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Super grids typically use high-voltage direct current (HVDC) to transmit electricity long distances.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The latest generation of HVDC power lines can transmit energy with losses of only 1.6% per 1000 km.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Electric utilities between regions are many times interconnected for improved economy and reliability.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Electrical interconnectors allow for economies of scale, allowing energy to be purchased from large, efficient sources.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Utilities can draw power from generator reserves from a different region to ensure continuing, reliable power and diversify their loads.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Interconnection also allows regions to have access to cheap bulk energy by receiving power from different sources.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] For example, one region may be producing cheap hydro power during high water seasons, but in low water seasons, another area may be producing cheaper power through wind, allowing both regions to access cheaper energy sources from one another during different times of the year.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Neighboring utilities also help others to maintain the overall system frequency and also help manage tie transfers between utility regions.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Electricity Interconnection Level (EIL) of a grid is the ratio of the total interconnector power to the grid divided by the installed production capacity of the grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Within the EU, it has set a target of national grids reaching 10% by 2020, and 15% by 2030.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Electricity generation is the process of generating electric power at power stations.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] This is done ultimately from sources of primary energy typically with electromechanical generators driven by heat engines from fossil, nuclear, and geothermal sources, or driven by the kinetic energy of water or wind.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Other power sources are photovoltaics driven by solar insolation, and grid batteries.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The sum of the power outputs of generators on the grid is the production of the grid, typically measured in gigawatts (GW).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Electric power transmission is the bulk movement of electrical energy from a generating site, via a web of interconnected lines, to an electrical substation, from which is connected to the distribution system.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] This networked system of connections is distinct from the local wiring between high-voltage substations and customers.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Transmission networks are built with redundant pathways to prevent a single point of failure.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In case of line failures this redundancy allows power to be simply rerouted while repairs are done.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Because the power is often generated far from where it is consumed, the transmission system can cover great distances.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] For a given amount of power, transmission efficiency is greater at higher voltages and lower currents.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Therefore, voltages are stepped up at the generating station, and stepped down at local substations for distribution to customers.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Three-phase, compared to single-phase, can deliver much more power for a given amount of wire, since the neutral and ground wires are shared.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Further, three-phase generators and motors are more efficient than their single-phase counterparts.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] However, for conventional conductors one of the main losses are resistive losses which are a square law on current, and depend on distance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] High voltage AC transmission lines can lose 1–4% per hundred miles.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] However, high-voltage direct current can have half the losses of AC.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Over very long distances, these efficiencies can offset the additional cost of the required AC/DC converter stations at each end.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Substations may perform many different functions but usually transform voltage from low to high (step up) and from high to low (step down).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Between the generator and the final consumer, the voltage may be transformed several times.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Distribution is the final stage in the delivery of power; it carries electricity from the transmission system to individual consumers.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Substations connect to the transmission system and lower the transmission voltage to medium voltage ranging between 2 kV and 35 kV.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] But the voltage levels varies very much between different countries, in Sweden medium voltage are normally 10 kV between 20 kV.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Primary distribution lines carry this medium voltage power to distribution transformers located near the customer's premises.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Distribution transformers again lower the voltage to the utilization voltage.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Customers demanding a much larger amount of power may be connected directly to the primary distribution level or the subtransmission level.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Distribution networks are divided into two types, radial or network.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In cities and towns of North America, the grid tends to follow the classic *radially fed* design.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] A substation receives its power from the transmission network, the power is stepped down with a transformer and sent to a bus from which feeders fan out in all directions across the countryside.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] These feeders carry three-phase power, and tend to follow the major streets near the substation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] As the distance from the substation grows, the fanout continues as smaller laterals spread out to cover areas missed by the feeders.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] This tree-like structure grows outward from the substation, but for reliability reasons, usually contains at least one unused backup connection to a nearby substation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] This connection can be enabled in case of an emergency, so that a portion of a substation's service territory can be alternatively fed by another substation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] As of 2020, the largest form of grid energy storage is dammed hydroelectricity, with both conventional hydroelectric generation as well as pumped storage hydroelectricity.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Developments in battery storage have enabled commercially viable projects to store energy during peak production and release during peak demand, and for use when production unexpectedly falls giving time for slower responding resources to be brought online.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Two alternatives to grid storage are the use of peaking power plants to fill in supply gaps and demand response to shift load to other times.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The demand, or load on an electrical grid is the total electrical power being removed by the users of the grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The graph of the demand over time is called the *demand curve*.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Baseload is the minimum load on the grid over any given period, peak demand is the maximum load.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Historically, baseload was commonly met by equipment that was relatively cheap to run, that ran continuously for weeks or months at a time, but globally this is becoming less common.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The extra peak demand requirements are sometimes produced by expensive peaking plants that are generators optimised to come on-line quickly but these too are becoming less common.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] However, if the demand of electricity exceeds the capacity of a local power grid, it will cause safety issues like burning out.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Grids are designed to supply electricity to their customers at largely constant voltages.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] This has to be achieved with varying demand, variable reactive loads, and even nonlinear loads, with electricity provided by generators and distribution and transmission equipment that are not perfectly reliable.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Often grids use tap changers on transformers near to the consumers to adjust the voltage and keep it within specification.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In a synchronous grid all the generators must run at the same frequency, and must stay very nearly in phase with each other and the grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Generation and consumption must be balanced across the entire grid, because energy is consumed as it is produced.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] For rotating generators, a local governor regulates the driving torque, maintaining almost constant rotation speed as loading changes.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Energy is stored in the immediate short term by the rotational kinetic energy of the generators.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Although the speed is kept largely constant, small deviations from the nominal system frequency are very important in regulating individual generators and are used as a way of assessing the equilibrium of the grid as a whole.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] When the grid is lightly loaded the grid frequency runs above the nominal frequency, and this is taken as an indication by Automatic generation control (AGC) systems across the network that generators should reduce their output.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Conversely, when the grid is heavily loaded, the frequency naturally slows, and governors adjust their generators so that more power is output (droop speed control).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] When generators have identical droop speed control settings it ensures that multiple parallel generators with the same settings share load in proportion to their rating.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In addition, there's often central control, which can change the parameters of the AGC systems over timescales of a minute or longer to further adjust the regional network flows and the operating frequency of the grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] For timekeeping purposes, the nominal frequency will be allowed to vary in the short term, but is adjusted to prevent line-operated clocks from gaining or losing significant time over the course of a whole 24 hour period.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Neighbouring grids that are not directly connected are almost always out-of-phase with each other.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Instead, high-voltage direct current lines or variable-frequency transformers are used, which allow two out-of-phase synchronous grids to share power.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The sum of the maximum power outputs (nameplate capacity) of the generators attached to an electrical grid might be considered to be the capacity of the grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] However, in practice, they are never run flat out simultaneously.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Typically, some generators are kept running at lower output powers (spinning reserve) to deal with failures as well as variation in demand.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In addition generators can be off-line for maintenance or other reasons, such as availability of energy inputs (fuel, water, wind, sun etc.) or pollution constraints.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Most grid codes specify that the load is shared between the generators in merit order according to their marginal cost (i.e. cheapest first) and sometimes their environmental impact.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Thus cheap electricity providers tend to be run flat out almost all the time, and the more expensive producers are only run when necessary.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] A central authority is usually designated to facilitate communication and develop protocols to maintain a stable grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] For example, the North American Electric Reliability Corporation gained binding powers in the United States in 2006, and has advisory powers in the applicable parts of Canada and Mexico.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The U.S. government has also designated National Interest Electric Transmission Corridors, where it believes transmission bottlenecks have developed.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Where multiple utilities own generators connected to one electrical grid power pools are often formed which have agreements about responsibilities.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Each grid may have a system operator that is responsible for day-to-day running of one or more grids.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Failures are usually associated with generators or power transmission lines tripping circuit breakers due to faults leading to a loss of generation capacity for customers, or excess demand.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] This will often cause the frequency to reduce, and the remaining generators will react and together attempt to stabilize above the minimum.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] If that is not possible then a number of scenarios can occur.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] A large failure in one part of the grid—unless quickly compensated for—can cause current to re-route itself to flow from the remaining generators to consumers over transmission lines of insufficient capacity, causing further failures.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] One downside to a widely connected grid is thus the possibility of cascading failure and widespread power outage.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] A *brownout* is an intentional or unintentional drop in voltage in an electrical power supply system.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Intentional brownouts are used for load reduction in an emergency.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The reduction lasts for minutes or hours, as opposed to short-term voltage sag (or dip).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The term brownout comes from the dimming experienced by incandescent lighting when the voltage sags.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] A voltage reduction may be an effect of disruption of an electrical grid, or may occasionally be imposed in an effort to reduce load and prevent a power outage, known as a blackout.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] A *power outage* (also called a *power cut*, a *power out*, a *power blackout*, *power failure* or a *blackout*) is a loss of the electric power to a particular area.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Power failures can be caused by faults at power stations, damage to electric transmission lines, substations or other parts of the distribution system, a short circuit, cascading failure, fuse or circuit breaker operation, and human error.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Power failures are particularly critical at sites where the environment and public safety are at risk.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Institutions such as hospitals, sewage treatment plants, mines, shelters and the like will usually have backup power sources such as standby generators, which will automatically start up when electrical power is lost.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Other critical systems, such as telecommunication, are also required to have emergency power.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The battery room of a telephone exchange usually has arrays of lead–acid batteries for backup and also a socket for connecting a generator during extended periods of outage.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Electrical generation and transmission systems may not always meet peak demand requirements— the greatest amount of electricity required by all utility customers within a given region.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In these situations, overall demand must be lowered, either by turning off service to some devices or cutting back the supply voltage (brownouts), in order to prevent uncontrolled service disruptions such as power outages (widespread blackouts) or equipment damage.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Utilities may impose load shedding on service areas via targeted blackouts, rolling blackouts or by agreements with specific high-use industrial consumers to turn off equipment at times of system-wide peak demand.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] A *black start* is the process of restoring an electric power station or a part of an electric grid to operation without relying on the external electric power transmission network to recover from a total or partial shutdown.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Normally, the electric power used within the plant is provided from the station's own generators.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] If all of the plant's main generators are shut down, station service power is provided by drawing power from the grid through the plant's transmission line.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] However, during a wide-area outage, off-site power from the grid is not available.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In the absence of grid power, a so-called black start needs to be performed to bootstrap the power grid into operation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] To provide a black start, some power stations have small diesel generators, normally called the *black start diesel generator* (BSDG), which can be used to start larger generators (of several megawatts capacity), which in turn can be used to start the main power station generators.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Generating plants using steam turbines require station service power of up to 10% of their capacity for boiler feedwater pumps, boiler forced-draft combustion air blowers, and for fuel preparation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] It is uneconomical to provide such a large standby capacity at each station, so black-start power must be provided over designated tie lines from another station.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Often hydroelectric power plants are designated as the black-start sources to restore network interconnections.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] A hydroelectric station needs very little initial power to start (just enough to open the intake gates and provide excitation current to the generator field coils), and can put a large block of power on line very quickly to allow start-up of fossil-fuel or nuclear stations.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Certain types of combustion turbine can be configured for black start, providing another option in places without suitable hydroelectric plants.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In 2017 a utility in Southern California has successfully demonstrated the use of a battery energy storage system to provide a black start, firing up a combined cycle gas turbine from an idle state.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Despite novel institutional arrangements and network designs, power delivery infrastructures is experiencing aging across the developed world.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Demand response is a grid management technique where retail or wholesale customers are requested or incentivised either electronically or manually to reduce their load.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Currently, transmission grid operators use demand response to request load reduction from major energy users such as industrial plants.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Technologies such as smart metering can encourage customers to use power when electricity is plentiful by allowing for variable pricing.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The smart grid is an enhancement of the 20th century electrical grid, using two-way communications and distributed so-called intelligent devices.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Two-way flows of electricity and information could improve the delivery network.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Research is mainly focused on three systems of a smart grid – the infrastructure system, the management system, and the protection system.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Electronic power conditioning and control of the production and distribution of electricity are important aspects of the smart grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The smart grid represents the full suite of current and proposed responses to the challenges of electricity supply.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Numerous contributions to the overall improvement of energy infrastructure efficiency are anticipated from the deployment of smart grid technology, in particular including demand-side management.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The improved flexibility of the smart grid permits greater penetration of highly variable renewable energy sources such as solar power and wind power, even without the addition of energy storage.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Smart grids could also monitor/control residential devices that are noncritical during periods of peak power consumption, and return their function during nonpeak hours.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Concerns with smart grid technology mostly focus on smart meters, items enabled by them, and general security issues.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Roll-out of smart grid technology also implies a fundamental re-engineering of the electricity services industry, although typical usage of the term is focused on the technical infrastructure.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Smart grid policy is organized in Europe as Smart Grid European Technology Platform.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Policy in the United States is described in Title 42 of the United States Code.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Smart grids are not to be confused with sector coupled smart energy systems, as smart grids primarily refers to the power sector, while smart energy system use an integrated holistic focus which also includes other sectors of the energy system with the intent to create synergies between them.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Resistance to distributed generation among grid operators may encourage providers to leave the grid and instead distribute power to smaller geographies.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The Rocky Mountain Institute and other studies foresee widescale grid defection.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] However, grid defection may be less likely in places such as Germany that have greater power demands in the winter.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Early electric energy was produced near the device or service requiring that energy.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In the 1880s, electricity competed with steam, hydraulics, and especially coal gas.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Coal gas was first produced on customer's premises but later evolved into gasification plants that enjoyed economies of scale.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In the industrialized world, cities had networks of piped gas, used for lighting.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] But gas lamps produced poor light, wasted heat, made rooms hot and smoky, and gave off hydrogen and carbon monoxide.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In the 1880s electric lighting soon became advantageous compared to gas lighting.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Electric utility companies established central stations to take advantage of economies of scale and moved to centralized power generation, distribution, and system management.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] After the war of the currents was settled in favor of AC power, with long-distance power transmission it became possible to interconnect stations to balance the loads and improve load factors.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Historically, transmission and distribution lines were owned by the same company, but starting in the 1990s, many countries have liberalized the regulation of the electricity market in ways that have led to the separation of the electricity transmission business from the distribution business.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In the United Kingdom, Charles Merz, of the Merz & McLellan consulting partnership, built the Neptune Bank Power Station near Newcastle upon Tyne in 1901, and by 1912 had developed into the largest integrated power system in Europe.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Merz was appointed head of a parliamentary committee and his findings led to the Williamson Report of 1918, which in turn created the Electricity (Supply) Act 1919.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The bill was the first step towards an integrated electricity system.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In 1925 the Weir Committee recommended the creation of a "national gridiron" and so the Electricity (Supply) Act 1926 created the Central Electricity Board (CEB).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The CEB standardized the nation's electricity supply and established the first synchronized AC grid, running at 132 kilovolts and 50 hertz but initially operated as regional grids.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] After brief overnight interconnection in 1937 they permanently and officially joined in 1938 becoming the UK National Grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In France, electrification began in the 1900s, with 700 communes in 1919, and 36,528 in 1938.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] At the same time, these close networks began to interconnect: Paris in 1907 at 12 kV, the Pyrénées in 1923 at 150 kV, and finally almost all of the country interconnected by 1938 at 220 kV.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In 1946, the grid was the world's most dense.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] That year the state nationalised the industry, by uniting the private companies as Électricité de France.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The frequency was standardised at 50 Hz, and the 225 kV network replaced 110 kV and 120 kV.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Since 1956, service voltage has been standardised at 220/380 V, replacing the previous 127/220 V.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] During the 1970s, the 400 kV network, the new European standard, was implemented.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Starting on May 29, 1986, the end user service voltage will progressively change to 230/400 V ±10%.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In the United States in the 1920s, utilities formed joint-operations to share peak load coverage and backup power.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In 1934, with the passage of the Public Utility Holding Company Act (U.S.), electric utilities were recognized as public goods of importance and were given outlined restrictions and regulatory oversight of their operations.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The Energy Policy Act of 1992 required transmission line owners to allow electric generation companies open access to their network and led to a restructuring of how the electric industry operated in an effort to create competition in power generation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] No longer were electric utilities built as vertical monopolies, where generation, transmission and distribution were handled by a single company.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] Now, the three stages could be split among various companies, in an effort to provide fair access to high voltage transmission.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] The Energy Policy Act of 2005 allowed incentives and loan guarantees for alternative energy production and advance innovative technologies that avoided greenhouse emissions.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In China, electrification began in the 1950s.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In August 1961, the electrification of the Baoji-Fengzhou section of the Baocheng Railway was completed and delivered for operation, becoming China's first electrified railway.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] From 1958 to 1998, China's electrified railway reached 6,200 miles (10,000 kilometres).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] As of the end of 2017, this number has reached 54,000 miles (87,000 kilometres).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/electrical-grid] In the current railway electrification system of China, State Grid Corporation of China—Archived 2021-12-21 at the Wayback Machine—is an important power supplier.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] A **phasor measurement unit** (**PMU**) is a device used to estimate the magnitude and phase angle of an electrical phasor quantity (such as voltage or current) in the electricity grid using a common time source for synchronization.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Time synchronization is usually provided by GPS or IEEE 1588 Precision Time Protocol, which allows synchronized real-time measurements of multiple remote points on the grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] PMUs are capable of capturing samples from a waveform in quick succession and reconstructing the phasor quantity, made up of an angle measurement and a magnitude measurement.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The resulting measurement is known as a **synchrophasor**.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] These time synchronized measurements are important because if the grid’s supply and demand are not perfectly matched, frequency imbalances can cause stress on the grid, which is a potential cause for power outages.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] PMUs can also be used to measure the frequency in the power grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] A typical commercial PMU can report measurements with very high temporal resolution, up to 120 measurements per second.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] This helps engineers in analyzing dynamic events in the grid which is not possible with traditional SCADA measurements that generate one measurement every 2 or 4 seconds.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Therefore, PMUs equip utilities with enhanced monitoring and control capabilities and are considered to be one of the most important measuring devices in the future of power systems.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] A PMU can be a dedicated device, or the PMU function can be incorporated into a protective relay or other device.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] In 1893, Charles Proteus Steinmetz presented a paper on simplified mathematical description of the waveforms of alternating current electricity.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Steinmetz called his representation a phasor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] With the invention of phasor measurement units (PMU) in 1988 by Dr.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Thorp at Virginia Tech, Steinmetz’s technique of phasor calculation evolved into the calculation of real time phasor measurements that are synchronized to an absolute time reference provided by the Global Positioning System.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] We therefore refer to synchronized phasor measurements as *synchrophasors*.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Early prototypes of the PMU were built at Virginia Tech, and Macrodyne built the first PMU (model 1690) in 1992.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] With the increasing growth of distributed energy resources on the power grid, more observability and control systems will be needed to accurately monitor power flow.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Historically, power has been delivered in a uni-directional fashion through passive components to customers, but now that customers can generate their own power with technologies such as solar PV, this is changing into a bidirectional system for distribution systems.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] With this change it is imperative that transmission and distribution networks are continuously being observed through advanced sensor technology, such as ––PMUs and uPMUs.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] In simple terms, the public electric grid that a power company operates was originally designed to take power from a single source: the operating company's generators and power plants, and feed it into the grid, where the customers consume the power.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Now, some customers are operating power generating devices (solar panels, wind turbines, etc.) and to save costs (or to generate income) are also feeding power back into the grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Depending on the region, feeding power back into the grid may be done through net metering.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Because of this process, voltage and current must be measured and regulated in order to ensure the power going into the grid is of the quality and standard that customer equipment expects (as seen through metrics such as frequency, phase synchronicity, and voltage).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] If this is not done, as Rob Landley puts it, "people's light bulbs start exploding." This measurement function is what these devices do.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] A PMU can measure 50/60 Hz AC waveforms (voltages and currents) typically at a rate of 48 samples per cycle making them effective at detecting fluctuations in voltage or current at less than one cycle.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] However, when the frequency does not oscillate around or near 50/60 Hz, PMUs are not able to accurately reconstruct these waveforms.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Phasor measurements from PMU’s are constructed from cosine waves, that follow the structure below.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The A in this function is a scalar value, that is most often described as voltage or current magnitude (for PMU measurements).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The θ is the phase angle offset from some defined starting position, and the ω is the angular frequency of the wave form (usually 2π50 radians/second or 2π60 radians/second).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] In most cases PMUs only measure the voltage magnitude and the phase angle, and assume that the angular frequency is a constant.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Because this frequency is assumed constant, it is disregarded in the phasor measurement.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] PMU’s measurements are a mathematical fitting problem, where the measurements are being fit to a sinusoidal curve.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Thus, when the waveform is non-sinusoidal, the PMU is unable to fit it exactly.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The less sinusoidal the waveform is, such as grid behavior during a voltage sag or fault, the worse the phasor representation becomes.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The analog AC waveforms detected by the PMU are digitized by an analog-to-digital converter for each phase.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] A phase-locked oscillator along with a Global Positioning System (GPS) reference source provides the needed high-speed synchronized sampling with 1 microsecond accuracy.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] However, PMUs can take in multiple time sources including non-GPS references as long as they are all calibrated and working synchronously.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The resultant time-stamped phasors can be transmitted to a local or remote receiver at rates up to 120 samples per second.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Being able to see time synchronized measurements over a large area is helpful in examining how the grid operates at large, and determining which parts of the grid are affected by different disturbances.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Historically, only small numbers of PMUs have been used to monitor transmission lines with acceptable errors of around 1%.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] These were simply coarser devices installed to prevent catastrophic blackouts.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Now, with the invention of micro-synchronous phasor technology, many more of them are desired to be installed on distribution networks where power can be monitored at a very high degree of precision.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] This high degree of precision creates the ability to drastically improve system visibility and implement smart and preventative control strategies.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] No longer are PMUs just required at sub-stations, but are required at several places in the network including tap-changing transformers, complex loads, and PV generation buses.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] While PMUs are generally used on transmission systems, new research is being done on the effectiveness of micro-PMUs for distribution systems.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Transmission systems generally have voltage that is at least an order of magnitude higher than distribution systems (between 12kV and 500kV while distribution runs at 12kV and lower).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] This means that transmission systems can have less precise measurements without compromising the accuracy of the measurement.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] However, distribution systems need more precision in order to improve accuracy, which is the benefit of uPMUs. uPMUs decrease the error of the phase angle measurements on the line from ±1° to ±0.05°, giving a better representation of the true angle value.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The “micro” term in front of the PMU simply means it is a more precise measurement.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] A phasor is a complex number that represents both the magnitude and phase angle of the sine waves found in electricity.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Phasor measurements that occur at the same time over any distance are called "synchrophasors".
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] While it is commonplace for the terms "PMU" and "synchrophasor" to be used interchangeably they actually represent two separate technical meanings.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] A synchrophasor is the metered value whereas the PMU is the metering device.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] In typical applications, phasor measurement units are sampled from widely dispersed locations in the power system network and synchronized from the common time source of a Global Positioning System (GPS) radio clock.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Synchrophasor technology provides a tool for system operators and planners to measure the state of the electrical system (over many points)and manage power quality.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] PMUs measure voltages and currents at principal intersecting locations (critical substations) on a power grid and can output accurately time-stamped voltage and current phasors.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Because these phasors are truly synchronized, synchronized comparison of two quantities is possible in real time.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] These comparisons can be used to assess system conditions-such as; frequency changes, MW, MVARs, kVolts, etc.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The monitored points are preselected through various studies to make extremely accurate phase angle measurements to indicate shifts in system (grid) stability.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The phasor data is collected either on-site or at centralized locations using Phasor Data Concentrator technologies.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The data is then transmitted to a regional monitoring system which is maintained by the local Independent System Operator (ISO).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] These ISO's will monitor phasor data from individual PMU's or from as many as 150 PMU's — this monitoring provides an accurate means of establishing controls for power flow from multiple energy generation sources (nuclear, coal, wind, etc.).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The technology has the potential to change the economics of power delivery by allowing increased power flow over existing lines.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Synchrophasor data could be used to allow power flow up to a line's dynamic limit instead of to its worst-case limit.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Synchrophasor technology will usher in a new process for establishing centralized and selective controls for the flow of electrical energy over the grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] These controls will affect both large scale (multiple-states) and individual transmission line sections at intersecting substations.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Transmission line congestion (over-loading), protection, and control will therefore be improved on a multiple region scale (US, Canada, Mexico) through interconnecting ISO's.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] A phasor network consists of phasor measurement units (PMUs) dispersed throughout the electricity system, Phasor Data Concentrators (PDC) to collect the information and a Supervisory Control And Data Acquisition (SCADA) system at the central control facility.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Such a network is used in Wide Area Measurement Systems (WAMS), the first of which began in 2000 by the Bonneville Power Administration.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The complete network requires rapid data transfer within the frequency of sampling of the phasor data.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] GPS time stamping can provide a theoretical accuracy of synchronization better than 1 microsecond.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] "Clocks need to be accurate to ± 500 nanoseconds to provide the one microsecond time standard needed by each device performing synchrophasor measurement." For 60 Hz systems, PMUs must deliver between 10 and 30 synchronous reports per second depending on the application.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The PDC correlates the data, and controls and monitors the PMUs (from a dozen up to 60).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] At the central control facility, the SCADA system presents system wide data on all generators and substations in the system every 2 to 10 seconds.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] PMUs often use phone lines to connect to PDCs, which then send data to the SCADA or Wide Area Measurement System (WAMS) server.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Additionally, PMUs can use ubiquitous mobile (cellular) networks for data transfer (GPRS, UMTS), which allows potential savings in infrastructure and deployment costs, at the expense of a larger data reporting latency.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] However, the introduced data latency makes such systems more suitable for R&D measurement campaigns and near real-time monitoring, and limits their use in real-time protective systems.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] PMUs from multiple vendors can yield inaccurate readings.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] In one test, readings differed by 47 microseconds – or a difference of 1 degree of 60 Hz- an unacceptable variance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] China's solution to the problem was to build all its own PMUs adhering to its own specifications and standards so there would be no multi-vendor source of conflicts, standards, protocols, or performance characteristics.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Installation of a typical 10 Phasor PMU is a simple process.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] A phasor will be either a 3 phase voltage or a 3 phase current.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Each phasor will, therefore, require 3 separate electrical connections (one for each phase).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Typically an electrical engineer designs the installation and interconnection of a PMU at a substation or at a generation plant.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Substation personnel will bolt an equipment rack to the floor of the substation following established seismic mounting requirements.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Then the PMU along with a modem and other support equipment will be mounted on the equipment rack.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] They will also install the Global Positioning Satellite (GPS) antenna on the roof of the substation per manufacturer instructions.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Substation personnel will also install "shunts" in all Current transformer (CT) secondary circuits that are to be measured.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The PMU will also require communication circuit connection (Modem if using 4-wire connection or Ethernet for network connection).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Load shedding and other load control techniques such as demand response mechanisms to manage a power system.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Increase the reliability of the power grid by detecting faults early, allowing for isolation of operative system, and the prevention of power outages.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Increase power quality by precise analysis and automated correction of sources of system degradation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Wide area measurement and control through state estimation, in very wide area super grids, regional transmission networks, and local distribution grids.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Phasor measurement technology and synchronized time stamping can be used for Security improvement through synchronized encryptions like trusted sensing base.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Cyber attack recognition by verifying data between the SCADA system and the PMU data.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Distribution State Estimation and Model Verification.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Ability to calculate impedances of loads, distribution lines, verify voltage magnitude and delta angles based on mathematical state models.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Events such as various types of faults, tap changes, switching events, circuit protection devices.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Machine learning and signal classification methods can be used to develop algorithms to identify these significant events.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] Microgrid applications––islanding or deciding where to detach from the grid, load and generation matching, and resynchronization with the main grid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The IEEE 1344 standard for synchrophasors was completed in 1995, and reaffirmed in 2001.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] In 2005, it was replaced by IEEE C37.118-2005, which was a complete revision and dealt with issues concerning use of PMUs in electric power systems.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] The specification describes standards for measurement, the method of quantifying the measurements, testing & certification requirements for verifying accuracy, and data transmission format and protocol for real-time data communication.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] This standard was not comprehensive- it did not attempt to address all factors that PMUs can detect in power system dynamic activity.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] A new version of the standard was released in December 2011, which split the IEEE C37.118-2005 standard into two parts: C37.118-1 dealing with the phasor estimation & C37.118-2 the communications protocol.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] It also introduced two classifications of PMU, M — measurement & P — protection.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] M class is close in performance requirements to that in the original 2005 standard, primarily for steady state measurement.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] P class has relaxed some performance requirements and is intended to capture dynamic system behavior.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] An amendment to C37.118.1 was released in 2014.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor-measurement-unit] IEEE C37.118.1a-2014 modified PMU performance requirements that were not considered achievable.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] In physics and engineering, a **phasor** (a portmanteau of **phase vector**) is a complex number representing a sinusoidal function whose amplitude A and initial phase θ are time-invariant and whose angular frequency ω is fixed.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] It is related to a more general concept called analytic representation, which decomposes a sinusoid into the product of a complex constant and a factor depending on time and frequency.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The complex constant, which depends on amplitude and phase, is known as a **phasor**, or **complex amplitude**, and (in older texts) **sinor** or even **complexor**.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] A common application is in the steady-state analysis of an electrical network powered by time varying current where all signals are assumed to be sinusoidal with a common frequency.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Phasor representation allows the analyst to represent the amplitude and phase of the signal using a single complex number.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The only difference in their analytic representations is the complex amplitude (phasor).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] A linear combination of such functions can be represented as a linear combination of phasors (known as **phasor arithmetic** or **phasor algebra**) and the time/frequency dependent factor that they all have in common.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The origin of the term phasor rightfully suggests that a (diagrammatic) calculus somewhat similar to that possible for vectors is possible for phasors as well.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The originator of the phasor transform was Charles Proteus Steinmetz working at General Electric in the late 19th century.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] He got his inspiration from Oliver Heaviside.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Heaviside's operational calculus was modified so that the variable p becomes jω.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The complex number j has simple meaning: phase shift.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Glossing over some mathematical details, the phasor transform can also be seen as a particular case of the Laplace transform (limited to a single frequency), which, in contrast to phasor representation, can be used to (simultaneously) derive the transient response of an RLC circuit.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] However, the Laplace transform is mathematically more difficult to apply and the effort may be unjustified if only steady state analysis is required.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The angle may be stated in degrees with an implied conversion from degrees to radians.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Multiplication and division of complex numbers become straight forward through the phasor notation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] whose real part is the original sinusoid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The benefit of the complex representation is that linear operations with other complex representations produces a complex result whose real part reflects the same linear operations with the real parts of the other complex sinusoids.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Furthermore, all the mathematics can be done with just the phasors $Ae^{i\theta },$ and the common factor $e^{i\omega t}$ is reinserted prior to the real part of the result.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The function $Ae^{i(\omega t+\theta )}$ is an *analytic representation* of $A\cos(\omega t+\theta ).$ Figure 2 depicts it as a rotating vector in the complex plane.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] It is sometimes convenient to refer to the entire function as a *phasor*, as we do in the next section.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Multiplication of the phasor $Ae^{i\theta }e^{i\omega t}$ by a complex constant, $Be^{i\phi }$ , produces another phasor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] In electronics, $Be^{i\phi }$ would represent an impedance, which is independent of time.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] In particular it is *not* the shorthand notation for another phasor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Multiplying a phasor current by an impedance produces a phasor voltage.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] But the product of two phasors (or squaring a phasor) would represent the product of two sinusoids, which is a non-linear operation that produces new frequency components.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Phasor notation can only represent systems with one frequency, such as a linear system stimulated by a sinusoid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The sum of multiple phasors produces another phasor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] A key point is that *A*3 and *θ*3 do not depend on *ω* or *t*, which is what makes phasor notation possible.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The time and frequency dependence can be suppressed and re-inserted into the outcome as long as the only operations used in between are ones that produce another phasor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Another way to view addition is that two **vectors** with coordinates [*A*1 cos(*ωt* + *θ*1), *A*1 sin(*ωt* + *θ*1)] and [*A*2 cos(*ωt* + *θ*2), *A*2 sin(*ωt* + *θ*2)] are added vectorially to produce a resultant vector with coordinates [*A*3 cos(*ωt* + *θ*3), *A*3 sin(*ωt* + *θ*3)] (see animation).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] In physics, this sort of addition occurs when sinusoids interfere with each other, constructively or destructively.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Clearly, the shape which satisfies these conditions is an equilateral triangle, so the angle between each phasor to the next is 120° (2π⁄3 radians), or one third of a wavelength *λ*⁄3.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] So the phase difference between each wave must also be 120°, as is the case in three-phase power.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] In the example of three waves, the phase difference between the first and the last wave was 240°, while for two waves destructive interference happens at 180°.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] In the limit of many waves, the phasors must form a circle for destructive interference, so that the first phasor is nearly parallel with the last.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] This means that for many sources, destructive interference happens when the first and last wave differ by 360 degrees, a full wavelength $\lambda$ .
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] This is why in single slit diffraction, the minima occur when light from the far edge travels a full wavelength further than the light from the near edge.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] As the single vector rotates in an anti-clockwise direction, its tip at point A will rotate one complete revolution of 360° or 2π radians representing one complete cycle.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] If the length of its moving tip is transferred at different angular intervals in time to a graph as shown above, a sinusoidal waveform would be drawn starting at the left with zero time.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Each position along the horizontal axis indicates the time that has elapsed since zero time, *t* = 0.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] When the vector is horizontal the tip of the vector represents the angles at 0°, 180°, and at 360°.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Likewise, when the tip of the vector is vertical it represents the positive peak value, (+*A*max) at 90° or π⁄2 and the negative peak value, (−*A*max) at 270° or 3π⁄2.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Then the time axis of the waveform represents the angle either in degrees or radians through which the phasor has moved.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] So we can say that a phasor represents a scaled voltage or current value of a rotating vector which is "frozen" at some point in time, (t) and in our example above, this is at an angle of 30°.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Sometimes when we are analysing alternating waveforms we may need to know the position of the phasor, representing the alternating quantity at some particular instant in time especially when we want to compare two different waveforms on the same axis.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] We have assumed in the waveform above that the waveform starts at time *t* = 0 with a corresponding phase angle in either degrees or radians.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] But if a second waveform starts to the left or to the right of this zero point, or if we want to represent in phasor notation the relationship between the two waveforms, then we will need to take into account this phase difference, *Φ* of the waveform.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Consider the diagram below from the previous Phase Difference tutorial.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The time derivative or integral of a phasor produces another phasor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Therefore, in phasor representation, the time derivative of a sinusoid becomes just multiplication by the constant ${\textstyle i\omega =e^{i\pi /2}\cdot \omega }$ .
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Similarly, integrating a phasor corresponds to multiplication by ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{i\omega }}={\frac {e^{-i\pi /2}}{\omega }}.}$ The time-dependent factor, $e^{i\omega t},$ is unaffected.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] When we solve a linear differential equation with phasor arithmetic, we are merely factoring $e^{i\omega t}$ out of all terms of the equation, and reinserting it into the answer.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] A quantity called complex impedance is the ratio of two phasors, which is not a phasor, because it does not correspond to a sinusoidally varying function.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] With phasors, the techniques for solving DC circuits can be applied to solve linear AC circuits.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Work with voltages and current as complex phasors.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] In an AC circuit we have real power (P) which is a representation of the average power into the circuit and reactive power (*Q*) which indicates power flowing back and forth.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] We can also define the complex power *S* = *P* + *jQ* and the apparent power which is the magnitude of S.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The power law for an AC circuit expressed in phasors is then *S* = *VI** (where *I** is the complex conjugate of *I*, and the magnitudes of the voltage and current phasors *V* and of *I* are the RMS values of the voltage and current, respectively).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Given this we can apply the techniques of analysis of resistive circuits with phasors to analyze single frequency linear AC circuits containing resistors, capacitors, and inductors.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] This solution method applies only to inputs that are sinusoidal and for solutions that are in steady state, i.e., after all transients have died out.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The concept is frequently involved in representing an electrical impedance.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] In this case, the phase angle is the phase difference between the voltage applied to the impedance and the current driven through it.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] In analysis of three-phase AC power systems, usually a set of phasors is defined as the three complex cube roots of unity, graphically represented as unit magnitudes at angles of 0, 120 and 240 degrees.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] By treating polyphase AC circuit quantities as phasors, balanced circuits can be simplified and unbalanced circuits can be treated as an algebraic combination of symmetrical components.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] This approach greatly simplifies the work required in electrical calculations of voltage drop, power flow, and short-circuit currents.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] In the context of power systems analysis, the phase angle is often given in degrees, and the magnitude in RMS value rather than the peak amplitude of the sinusoid.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The technique of synchrophasors uses digital instruments to measure the phasors representing transmission system voltages at widespread points in a transmission network.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Differences among the phasors indicate power flow and system stability.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The rotating frame picture using phasor can be a powerful tool to understand analog modulations such as amplitude modulation (and its variants) and frequency modulation.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] $x(t)=\operatorname {Re} \left(Ae^{i\theta }\cdot e^{i2\pi f_{0}t}\right),$ where the term in brackets is viewed as a rotating vector in the complex plane.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The phasor has length A , rotates anti-clockwise at a rate of $f_{0}$ revolutions per second, and at time $t=0$ makes an angle of $\theta$ with respect to the positive real axis.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The waveform $x(t)$ can then be viewed as a projection of this vector onto the real axis.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] A modulated waveform is represented by this phasor (the carrier) and two additional phasors (the modulation phasors).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] The two modulation phasors are phased such that their vector sum is always in phase with the carrier phasor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] An alternative representation is two phasors counter rotating around the end of the carrier phasor at a rate $f_{m}$ relative to the carrier phasor.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Frequency modulation is a similar representation except that the modulating phasors are not in phase with the carrier.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] In this case the vector sum of the modulating phasors is shifted 90° from the carrier phase.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/phasor] Strictly, frequency modulation representation requires additional small modulation phasors at $2f_{m},3f_{m}$ etc., but for most practical purposes these are ignored because their effect is very small.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] The **protection devices** are used to protect the power systems from faults by detecting the faults and taking *action* ("**tripping**").
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Anderson distinguishes the *reactionary devices*, like protective relays, that "clear" a fault by isolating it from the rest of system and *safeguard devices* that address the source of the hazard (for example, an emergency core cooling system of a nuclear reactor).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] As a discipline, power system protection mostly deals with the reactionary devices.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] With the exception of the breaker, the components of the protective device are frequently deployed in a redundant fashion.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] The objective of a protection scheme is to keep the power system stable by isolating only the components that are under fault, whilst leaving as much of the network as possible in operation, thus minimizing the loss of load.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] This property of the protection system is called *selectivity*.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] To achieve selectivity, the power system is subdivided into *protective zones*, each containing a power system component (generator, bus, transformer, transmission or distribution line, motor) that should be protected.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Each zone has its own protection device(s) and provides sensitivity to faults within its boundaries.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] If a fault were to occur in a given zone, necessary actions will be executed to isolate that zone from the entire system (all circuit breakers in a given zone with a fault will open in order to isolate the fault).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] The boundaries of zones overlap to leave no part of grid without protection, overlapped regions usually surround circuit breakers with two sets of instrument transformers and relays for each circuit breaker.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] The overlapping regions of sensitivity have a drawback of multiple relays possibly tripping when the fault is in the overlapped area.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] For example, unless special arrangements are made, a short circuit above the relay A, but still within the blue zone on the diagram, might cause overcurrent conditions in relays A, C, and D and cause them to trip, with the two latter trips being redundant.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] This can be avoided by using specialized relays (distance or directional ones) or by coordinating the relay actions using a communication channel ("pilot").
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] In any case, overlapped regions are designed to be as small as possible such that when a fault occurs in an overlap region and the two zones which encompass the fault are isolated, the sector of the power system.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] The power protection system needs to be resilient to its own malfunctions.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Thus it includes backup protection devices.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] For example if the fault is in the top left red zone, but outside the blue zone, it is expected to be handled by the "primary" relay A.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] If the relay A malfunctions and cannot clear the fault, the *backup relays* C and D in the adjacent (blue) zone will trip.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] This can be arranged without coordination (for example, the delay setting of C and D can be higher so they do not act if A succeeds in clearing the fault) or through coordination via a pilot.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] The term *local backup* is used when the backup relays are within the same zone as the "primary" one being duplicated.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Local back-up protection, like the primary protective device, will isolate the elements of the plant affected by the fault to clear the latter.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Adjacent-zone ("remote") back-up protection will generally isolate both the affected and unaffected items of plant to clear the fault.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Many pieces of the grid equipment can develop internal problems.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] For these devices, the faults can be classified into *internal* and *external*.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] As an example of the internal fault, a transformer might develop overpressure inside its containment vessel with the root cause (for example, local overheating) not triggering any other alarms.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] For the same transformer, an overload condition would represent an external fault.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] In the 21st century a lot of testing for abnormal conditions is performed by multifunctional numerical relays that use computers for calculations.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Individual measurements use cryptic identifiers from the ANSI device numbers list, like "50" for the "Instantaneous Overcurrent Relay" or "87L" for the "Segregated Line Current Differential".
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] High-voltage transmission lines typically form a mesh-like grid, so the current might be flowing into the fault from either direction, making the non-directional relays mostly unsuitable for protection, so the distance and pilot relays are typically used.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] The use of directional relays is not always possible.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] In a grounded neutral transmission line, the phase relays might detect and clear a ground fault.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] However, since almost all faults on high-voltage lines are of the one-phase-to-ground variety, specialized ground relays are used for quick reaction.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] These relay utilize the zero-sequence current for detection.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] During the normal operation, the zero-sequence current is very small, so a high current value that depends on the network configuration, not on the (varying) load, is a convenient and reliable indicator of a ground fault.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Generators are expensive and complex pieces of the grid equipment, thus the larger machines use tens of types of protection devices.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Practically every generator has the stator protection, usually using differential relays.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] The internal failures of generators are unusual, so the protective relays trips are very rare.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Not only the transformers are expensive, but it might take a long time to replace a failed large transformer.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Electrical protection of a transformer mostly uses the differential relays.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] This protection can be combined with the one of the busbar or generator.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] The low-voltage network generally relies upon fuses or low-voltage circuit breakers to remove both overload and earth faults.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Disturbance-monitoring equipment (DME) monitors and records system data pertaining to a fault.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Protection engineers define dependability as the tendency of the protection system to operate correctly for in-zone faults.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] They define security as the tendency not to operate for out-of-zone faults.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Both dependability and security are reliability issues.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Fault tree analysis is one tool with which a protection engineer can compare the relative reliability of proposed protection schemes.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Quantifying protection reliability is important for making the best decisions on improving a protection system, managing dependability versus security tradeoffs, and getting the best results for the least money.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] A quantitative understanding is essential in the competitive utility industry.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] There are two aspects of reliable operation of protection systems: dependability and security.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Dependability is the ability of the protection system to operate when called upon to remove a faulted element from the power system.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Security is the ability of the protection system to restrain itself from operating during an external fault.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/power-system-protection] Choosing the appropriate balance between security and dependability in designing the protection system requires engineering judgement and varies on a case-by-case basis.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] A **wide area synchronous grid** (also called an "**interconnection**" in North America) is a three-phase electric power grid that has regional scale or greater that operates at a synchronized utility frequency and is electrically tied together during normal system conditions.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Also known as *synchronous zones*, the most powerful is the Northern Chinese State Grid with 1,700 gigawatts (GW) of generation capacity, while the widest region served is that of the IPS/UPS system serving most countries of the former Soviet Union.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Synchronous grids with ample capacity facilitate electricity trading across wide areas.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] In the CESA system in 2008, over 350,000 megawatt hours were sold per day on the European Energy Exchange (EEX).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Each of the interconnects in North America is synchronized at a nominal 60 Hz, while those of Europe run at 50 Hz.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Wide area synchronous networks improve reliability and permit the pooling of resources.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Also, they can level out the load, which reduces the required generating capacity, allow more environmentally-friendly power to be employed; allow more diverse power generation schemes and permit economies of scale.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Wide area synchronous networks cannot be formed if the two networks to be linked are running at different frequencies or have significantly different standards.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] For example, in Japan, for historical reasons, the northern part of the country operates on 50 Hz, but the southern part uses 60 Hz.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] That makes it impossible to form a single synchronous network, which was problematic when the Fukushima Daiichi plant melted down.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Also, even when the networks have compatible standards, failure modes can be problematic.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Phase and current limitations can be reached, which can cause widespread outages.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] The issues are sometimes solved by adding HVDC links within the network to permit greater control during off-nominal events.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] As was discovered in the 2000–2001 California electricity crisis, there can be strong incentives among some market traders to create deliberate congestion and poor management of generation capacity on an interconnection network to inflate prices.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Increasing transmission capacity and expanding the market by uniting with neighbouring synchronous networks make such manipulations more difficult.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] In a synchronous grid, all the generators naturally lock together electrically and run at the same frequency, and stay very nearly in phase with each other.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] For rotating generators, a local governor regulates the driving torque and helps maintain a more or less constant speed as loading changes.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Droop speed control ensures that multiple parallel generators share load changes in proportion to their rating.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Generation and consumption must be balanced across the entire grid because energy is consumed as it is produced.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Small deviations from the nominal system frequency are very important in regulating individual generators and assessing the equilibrium of the grid as a whole.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] When the grid is heavily loaded, the frequency slows, and governors adjust their generators so that more power is output (droop speed control).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] When the grid is lightly loaded the grid frequency runs above the nominal frequency, and this is taken as an indication by Automatic Generation Control systems across the network that generators should reduce their output.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Where neighbouring grids, operating at different frequencies, need to be interconnected, a frequency converter is required.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] HVDC interconnectors, solid-state transformers or variable-frequency transformers links can connect two grids that operate at different frequencies or that are not maintaining synchronism.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Inertia in a synchronous grid is stored energy that a grid has available which can provide extra power for up to a few seconds to maintain the grid frequency.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Historically, this was provided only by the angular momentum of the generators, and gave the control circuits time to adjust their output to variations in loads, and sudden generator or distribution failures.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Inverters connected to HVDC usually have no inertia, but wind power can provide inertia, and solar and battery systems can provide synthetic inertia.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] In short circuit situations, it's important for a grid to be able to provide sufficient current to keep the voltage and frequency reasonably stable until circuit breakers can resolve the fault.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Many traditional generator systems had wires which could be overloaded for very short periods without damage, but inverters are not as able to deliver multiple times their rated load.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] The short circuit ratio can be calculated for each point on the grid, and if it is found to be too low, for steps to be taken to increase it to be above 1, which is considered stable.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] In 2018 Kosovo used more power than it generated due to a row with Serbia, leading to the phase in the whole synchronous grid of Continental Europe lagging behind what it should have been.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Over time, this caused synchronous electric clocks to become six minutes slow until the disagreement was resolved.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Historically, on the North American power transmission grid the Eastern and Western Interconnections were directly connected, and was at the time largest synchronous grid in the world, but this was found to be unstable, and they are now only DC interconnected.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Interconnectors such as High-voltage direct current lines, solid-state transformers or variable-frequency transformers can be used to connect two alternating current interconnection networks which are not necessarily synchronized with each other.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] This provides the benefit of interconnection without the need to synchronize an even wider area.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] For example, compare the wide area synchronous grid map of Europe (in the introduction) with the map of HVDC lines (here to the right).
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] Solid state transformers have larger losses than conventional transformers, but DC lines lack reactive impedance and overall HVDC lines have lower losses sending power over long distances within a synchronous grid, or between them.
[src:synchrophasor-pmu/wide-area-synchronous-grid] The Tres Amigas SuperStation aims to enable energy transfers and trading between the Eastern Interconnection and Western Interconnection using 30GW HVDC Interconnectors.
